    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the hydration conundrum! Your starter's hydration level might be a bit on the dry side, which could be why it's not bubbling much. A 50g flour to 50g water ratio gives you a 100% hydration, which is pretty standard for a starter. But if you want to make it more liquidy, you can try increasing the water slightly. Maybe go for a 60g flour to 55g water ratio next time. This should give you a 110% hydration starter, which can be more active and bubbly. Just keep in mind that a higher hydration starter might be a bit harder to handle, as it's more liquid and can be a bit messier. But don't worry, it's not a big deal! Just give it a little extra care. And remember, a sourdough starter is like a little goblin in a jar; it needs the right balance of moisture and flour to wake up and play. So, give it a little more water and see if it starts to stir things up!",
